thoughts.reasoning_problem:

Economic hardship refers to difficulty caused by having too little money or too few resources. Tom lives in a single-parent family. His dad has been out of work for more than a year.
Question: Based on the above information, is the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Tom can apply for financial aid from ETS to take the GRE test.
Options: A) True B) False C) Uncertain
raw_logic_programs:
Predicates:
Cost(x, y) ::: x costs y.
FinancialAid(x, y) ::: x provides financial aid to y.
EconomicHardship(x) ::: x has economic hardship.
SingleParentFamily(x) ::: x lives in a single-parent family.
OutOfWork(x, y) ::: x has been out of work for more than y.
GREApplicant(x) ::: x is a GRE applicant.
Premises:
Cost(GRE, 205) ::: It costs US $205 to take the GRE test.
∀x (GREApplicant(x) ∧ EconomicHardship(x) → FinancialAid(ETS, x)) ::: ETS provides financial aid to those GRE applicants who prove economic hardship.
∀x (EconomicHardship(x) ↔ (LittleMoney(x) ∨ FewResources(x))) ::: Economic hardship refers to difficulty caused by having too little money or too few resources.
SingleParentFamily(tom) ∧ OutOfWork(tomDad, year1) ::: Tom lives in a single-parent family. His dad has been out of work for more than a year.
Conclusion:
GREApplicant(tom) → FinancialAid(ETS, tom) ::: Tom can apply for financial aid from ETS to take the GRE test.
